As Player RED, I start with all the resources (100 Dollars), and Player BLUE has none. Since this is the first move and I have the upper hand, I can propose a trade that maximizes my utility while still incentivizing Player BLUE to accept. Since BLUE has no resources to offer, I can propose a trade where I give nothing (or minimal value) while securing the majority of the resources.

I will propose a trade where I give 1 Dollar to Player BLUE (symbolic to show "generosity" and encourage acceptance). Player BLUE has no resources to give, so the trade is one-sided in terms of dollars, but it ensures I keep 99 Dollars while maintaining a chance for BLUE to accept. If BLUE rejects, I lose nothing (since I still have 100 Dollars), but the game ends with both players losing resources. However, since BLUE has no resources, rejecting is irrational from their perspective if they want any outcome other than total loss.

This is a classic "ultimatum game" strategy: offer just enough to make acceptance rational for the other player while keeping as much as possible.

